<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-herons-formula" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Heron's Formula</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_dpquf2pe">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_xsmegu3c">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_c8qso4v7">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6shzdt51">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_34g2hb0s">
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                       <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lll0wpdr">Determine the area of a triangle using Heron's formula</li>
                       </ul> 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                      10  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                     <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                         40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Recognize that Heron’s Formula allows for area calculation using only side lengths, removing the need for a perpendicular height
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Practice calculating the area of a right-angled triangle using both <m>\frac{1}{2}*b*h</m> and Heron’s Formula to prove they yield the same result.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                         <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use Heron’s Formula to find the area of a triangular field where it is physically impossible to walk a straight line through the center to measure the height (e.g., due to thick crops or a pond).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <!-- <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_lll0wpdr">Determine the area of a triangle using Heron's formula</li>
        </ul> -->
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_04ujp0x1">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_1n6298tc">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hxav14ic">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_n6dlydaj">Work in pairs</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_dhbsswya">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_g2ssdn27">
                    This anchor activity guides learners from the familiar <m>\frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height}</m> formula to discovering Heron's Formula. Each pair should have a triangular surface (cutout, signboard, or drawn triangle) to measure.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_d9h5ejrh">
                    <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ox8b9jdy">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_f0j1uhm3">Begin by asking: "How do we find the area of a triangle?" — confirm learners recall the standard formula</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7jym5xs4">Then pose: "What if we don't know the height?" to motivate the need for Heron's Formula</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_tgt2ralu">Guide learners through measuring all three sides and computing the semi-perimeter</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_j5zim2v8">Let learners discover the formula before formalizing it — resist giving the answer too early</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_h0vfnfs5">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_pgtswtte">
                        
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_xpwvt804">
                        Pair up students and give each pair a triangular surface to measure. This could be:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_k2rjgk65">
                        <ul xml:id="auto_y230zou9">
                            <li xml:id="auto_11x6bpdm">
                                <p xml:id="auto_k0pzrjl1">
                                    A triangular classroom table
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_6t63w7am">
                                <p xml:id="auto_vtesuaqm">
                                   A triangular signboard 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_cunsjpm9">
                                <p xml:id="auto_48go97qz">
                                    A triangular cutout from paper
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_rn9na1x6">
                                <p xml:id="auto_b0gybeme">
                                    A drawn triangle on graph paper
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_j37k3oxw">
                                    <m>\textbf{Materials needed.}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1yg4jvn8">
                                <p xml:id="auto_qbbkgglh">
                                    Ruler
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_mrl7qtll">
                                <p xml:id="auto_zjn04gv1">
                                    Graph paper
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_zlq6ejns">
                                <p xml:id="auto_izj5yc6z">
                                    Calculator
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_zte1d6pf">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ists9fm4">
                                    String or measuring tape
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_y0lsbmcj">
                                <p xml:id="auto_1hte7p4x">
                                    Pre-cut paper triangles (optional)
                                </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_c0ubbuez">
                                <ol xml:id="auto_eklyrw64">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_vvr8ka1i">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_rlwlyzbc">
                                             Recall the Standard Triangle Area Formula
                                        </p>
                                    <p xml:id="auto_xrmkity3">
                                        <ul xml:id="auto_t8qtrmua">
                                            <li xml:id="auto_6dk83zhq">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_ydwtk0lq">
                                                    How do we find the area of a triangle?
                                                </p>
                                                <p xml:id="auto_l4zkrhhm">
                                                    Expected answer ; <m> a = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height}</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_jmudziv7">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_xqbvqhxu">
                                                    This method works only when we know the height.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_2qtlow9n">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_9i1gbrl7">
                                                    <m>\textbf{What if we don’t know the height?}</m>  Today, they will discover how to find the area <m>\textbf{only using side lengths}</m>.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_k6yhf36i">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_of42fhg8">
                                        Construct a Triangle and Introduce Semi-Perimeter 
                                    </p>
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ksrqvhlb">
                                        <ul xml:id="auto_eo7izocg">
                                            <li xml:id="auto_xfzfhgcf">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_iiystabw">
                                                     Draw a triangle with sides labeled as <m>\textbf{a, b} \, \text{and} \, \textbf{c}</m>. Using a ruler or measuring tape, measure the <m>\textbf{three sides of the triangle}</m> and record the lengths.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_ilr9obgz">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_500s19am">
                                                    Measure and calculate the semi-perimeter using:
                                                    <md>
                                                        <mrow>S =  \amp \frac{a+b+c} {2}</mrow>
                                                    </md>
                                                    This helps divide the triangle into manageable parts for the area calculation.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_eu6amntb">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_wzakh3rh">
                                         Express the<m>\textbf{ Area} </m> in Terms of the <m>\textbf{Semi-Perimeter.}</m>
                                    </p>
                                    <p xml:id="auto_20fwl0iz">
                                        <ul xml:id="auto_x1vak0r7">
                                            <li xml:id="auto_ovu5t74o">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_cqpm2jwe">
                                                    Use the right-angle criteria.i.e:
                                                </p>
                                                <p xml:id="auto_v83ow9gi">
                                                    <m>\textbf{Drop a perpendicular}</m> from <m>\textbf{one vertex to the opposite side}</m> (splitting the triangle into two right-angled triangles).
                                                </p>
                                                <p xml:id="auto_144fytxo">
                                                    Let’s call the base <m> \textbf{b}</m> and split it into two parts using the perpendicular.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_53bxjxg4">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_aas6eqsu">
                                                    Use the <m>\textbf{Pythagorean Theorem}</m> to express the height <m>h</m> in terms of <m>\textbf{ a, b,  c}.</m>
                                                </p>
                                                <p xml:id="auto_g2pmxvjg">
                                                    Instead of solving fully, guide students to realize that the height can be found using algebraic manipulation.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_ric6wmep">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_2zffihx1">
                                                    Introduce the <m>\textbf{squared form}</m> and take the <m>\textbf{square root}</m>:
                                                    <md>
                                                        <mrow> A= \amp \sqrt{S(S-a)(S-b)(S-c)} </mrow>
                                                    </md>
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_t809g9w9">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_0mu40zsj">
                                                    This is the final area using Heron’s Formula.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li xml:id="auto_k8rekkh1">
                                                <p xml:id="auto_czmd237w">
                                                    
                                                    In conclusion, Heron’s Formula is finding the area of any triangle using only its sides.

                                            </p>
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_73iu0dsf">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_tydoujh0">10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_5lo3xf98">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_f2a50x3z">Whole class</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_mxoyilb0">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_po7xm4ki">
                    Formalize the derivation of Heron's Formula using the insight content. Walk through the key steps on the board.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_7aiyl9e5">
                    <alert>Key Points to Emphasize:</alert>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ksugdcki">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_00vz9vpp">The semi-perimeter <m>s = \frac{a+b+c}{2}</m> is always the first step</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zgjmxvom">The formula <m>A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</m> works for <em>any</em> triangle — not just right-angled ones</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7snbvgtf">Show how dropping a perpendicular and using Pythagoras leads to the formula</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_p3049xd7">Stress careful arithmetic: compute each bracket <m>(s-a)</m>, <m>(s-b)</m>, <m>(s-c)</m> separately before multiplying</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2o29xzby">
                    <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> Learners may confuse the perimeter with the semi-perimeter. Remind them to divide by 2.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_1jbx8zkl">
            <p xml:id="auto_b9jtfqpo">
                We know that the area of a triangle can be calculated using:
                <me>
                    \textbf{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height}
                </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_0w0zd62y">
                Consider a triangle with sides <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>. Let side <m>c</m> be the base and drop a perpendicular height <m>h</m>.
            </p>

            <image width="45%">
                <latex-image label="heron-derivation-1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (5,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (2,3);

                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[dashed] (C) -- (2,0);

                        \node[left] at (A) {$A$};
                        \node[right] at (B) {$B$};
                        \node[above] at (C) {$C$};

                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$c$};
                        \node[left] at (1,1.5) {$a$};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,1.5) {$b$};
                        \node[right] at (2,1.3) {$h$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <p xml:id="auto_53foss5r">
                Then:
                <me>
                    \textbf{Area} = \frac{1}{2} c h
                </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_7drprdds">
                Using Pythagoras' Theorem on the two right triangles formed, we can express <m>h</m> in terms of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a58wv8y6">
                After algebraic manipulation and simplification, the area can be written purely in terms of the three sides.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_03r3bzl3">
                Let the semi-perimeter be:
                <me>
                    s = \frac{a + b + c}{2}
                </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_slmneycw">
                Substituting and simplifying leads to:
                <me>
                    \textbf{Area} = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_m7o8pk0h">
                This result is known as <term>Hero’s Formula</term>. It allows us to calculate the area of any triangle when all three sides are known, without needing the height.
            </p>
        </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_g2iesmgl">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ui8eluwe">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_bgsq6cdz">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_yd9ophx4">Individual work, then compare with a partner</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_jlxde77v">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_u9f7khb6">
                    Work through the textbook example on the board, pausing for students to attempt each step. Then assign the exercises for independent practice.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_8qvk8c9g">
                    <alert>Tips:</alert>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mdtdbfxg">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_xxfppue9">For the first example (5-5-3 isosceles triangle), note that the semi-perimeter is not a whole number — this is a good opportunity to practise working with fractions</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zlxjdtfx">Encourage learners to set out their working clearly: state <m>a, b, c</m>, compute <m>s</m>, then each factor</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_uvq7lvnf">For exercise questions involving unknowns, guide learners to set up the equation and solve</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_mv4jvw5j">
            <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_wdjsuzpi">
                If the length of the sides of a triangle <m>ABC</m> are <m>5</m> <em>inches</em>, <m>5</m> <em>inches</em> and <m>3</m> <em>inches</em>. Calculate its area using the heron's formula.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>triangle</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="triangle-two-in-exercise">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define coordinates for the isosceles triangle (sides 5, 5, 3)
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (1.5, 4.77); % height = sqrt(25 - 2.25)

                    % Draw the triangle
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                    % Label the sides
                    \node at (1.5, 0) [below] {3 in}; % side AB
                    \node at (0.5, 2.5) [left] {5 in}; % side AC
                    \node at (2.5, 2.5) [right] {5 in}; % side BC

                    % Label the vertices
                    \node at (A) [below left] {A};
                    \node at (B) [below right] {B};
                    \node at (C) [above] {C};
                    
                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_szgeckho">
                To find: Area of the triangle <m>ABC</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gu584sds">
                Given that <em>AB</em> <m>= 3</m> in, <em>BC</em> <m> = 5</m> in, <em>AC</em> <m>= 5</m> in.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7zd6lj7c">
                Using Heron's Formula,
                <md>
                <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_46kod7pq">
                <md>
                <mrow>s \amp = \frac{a + b + c}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_yym5k12w">
                <md>
                <mrow>s \amp = \frac{5+5+3}{2} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tcnm9lr6">
                <md>
                <mrow> \amp = \frac{13}{2} \, \text{in} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_v6hz0tey">
                Substitute in the values,
                <md>
                <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{\frac{13}{2}\left(\frac{13}{2} - 5\right)\left(\frac{13}{2} - 5\right)\left(\frac{13}{2} - 3\right)} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ia1m2ylu">
                <md>
                <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{\frac{13}{2} \times \frac{3}{2} \times \frac{3}{2} \times \frac{7}{2}} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x9tx5k4b">
                <md>
                <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{\frac{819}{16}} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nc1magqu">
                <md>
                <mrow> \amp = \frac{3\sqrt{91}}{4} \approx 7.15 \, \text{in}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                The area of the triangle is <m>\frac{3\sqrt{91}}{4} \approx 7.15 \, \text{in}^2</m>.
            </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment – Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_kaszxku7">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_59x8w324">5 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_02lzntmm">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_facbcnxz">Individual</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_exi8ro98">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_d9m7kx7j">
                    Students complete the exercise questions individually to demonstrate understanding of Heron's Formula.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-herons-formula">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-right-triangle">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_e7z1y6e7">
                    A right-angled triangle has sides <m>9</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm and <m>15</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mm9osb4g">
                    (a) Verify that the triangle satisfies the Pythagorean relationship.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1q627aa9">
                    (b) Find its area using both the standard formula and Heron's formula, and confirm the answers agree.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_t37yo4zt">Area <m>= 54 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_bmqs3kyk">
                    (a) Check: <m>9^2 + 12^2 = 81 + 144 = 225 = 15^2</m>. The triangle is right-angled.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_4892burm">
                    (b) <alert>Standard formula:</alert> Taking the two shorter sides as base and height,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 9 \times 12 = 54 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_h63m5uw5">
                    <alert>Heron's formula:</alert> Let <m>a = 9</m>, <m>b = 12</m>, <m>c = 15</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{9 + 12 + 15}{2} = 18</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{18(18-9)(18-12)(18-15)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{18 \times 9 \times 6 \times 3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{2916}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 54 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Both methods give the same area of <m>54 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-scalene">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_sv7tmqzq">
                    Find the area of a triangle with sides <m>7</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm and <m>9</m> cm using Heron's formula.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_6waauah4"><m>12\sqrt{5} \approx 26.83 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_m1zjhajd">
                    Let <m>a = 7</m>, <m>b = 8</m>, <m>c = 9</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{7 + 8 + 9}{2} = 12</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{12(12-7)(12-8)(12-9)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{12 \times 5 \times 4 \times 3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{720}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 12\sqrt{5} \approx 26.83 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-equilateral">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_uncfxmpl">
                    An equilateral triangle has side length <m>10</m> cm. Use Heron's formula to find its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_oyyninzf"><m>25\sqrt{3} \approx 43.30 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_z81nvyg4">
                    Since the triangle is equilateral, <m>a = b = c = 10</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{10 + 10 + 10}{2} = 15</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{15(15-10)(15-10)(15-10)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{15 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{1875}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 25\sqrt{3} \approx 43.30 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-plot-of-land">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_f6znurdz">
                    A triangular plot of land has sides measuring <m>50</m> m, <m>65</m> m and <m>75</m> m. Find the area of the land using Heron's formula.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_75lvjm4l"><m>\approx 1620.19 \, \text{m}^2</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_5fgzlghp">
                    Let <m>a = 50</m>, <m>b = 65</m>, <m>c = 75</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{50 + 65 + 75}{2} = 95</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{95(95-50)(95-65)(95-75)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{95 \times 45 \times 30 \times 20}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{2\,565\,000}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp \approx 1620.19 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-isosceles">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_7a7hkou4">
                    An isosceles triangle has two equal sides of length <m>13</m> cm and a base of <m>10</m> cm. Find its area using Heron's formula.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_1025apyo"><m>60 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_shs420mc">
                    Let <m>a = 13</m>, <m>b = 13</m>, <m>c = 10</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{13 + 13 + 10}{2} = 18</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{18(18-13)(18-13)(18-10)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{18 \times 5 \times 5 \times 8}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{3600}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 60 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-real-world">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_yh0hgdlo">
                    A farmer has a triangular piece of land with sides <m>120</m> m, <m>150</m> m and <m>200</m> m. If the cost of planting grass is KSh <m>45</m> per square metre, find the total cost of planting grass on the entire plot.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_v56koe3v"><m>\approx \text{KSh } 394\,348</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_7nzfo4od">
                    First find the area. Let <m>a = 120</m>, <m>b = 150</m>, <m>c = 200</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp = \frac{120 + 150 + 200}{2} = 235</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{235(235-120)(235-150)(235-200)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{235 \times 115 \times 85 \times 35}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{80\,413\,125}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp \approx 8763.29 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Total cost:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Cost} \amp = 8763.29 \times 45 \approx \text{KSh } 394\,348</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heron-find-side">
            <title>A Challenging Question </title>
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_e4dqwq1z">
                    A triangle has two sides of length <m>2</m> cm and <m>2</m> cm, and its area is <m>\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2</m>. Use Heron's formula to find the length of the third side.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p xml:id="auto_sz96e2n1">
                    You will need to use your quadratic identities from <xref ref="subsec-quadratic-identities"/>, and your factorisation skills from <xref ref="subsubsec-factorising-monic-quadratics"/>. If you encounter an expression in the form <m>c^4 + ac^2 + b = 0</m>, you can use the substitution <m>u = c^2</m> to transform it into a quadratic, and solve for <m>u</m>.
                </p>
            </hint>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_g2nnqk39"><m>2</m> cm or <m>2\sqrt{3}</m> cm</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_0w51sqw0">
                    Let <m>a = 2</m>, <m>b = 2</m>, and <m>c</m> be the unknown side. By Heron's formula,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    where <m>s = \frac{2 + 2 + c}{2} = \frac{4 + c}{2}</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_myl5bx18">
                    Since <m>A = \sqrt{3}</m>, we square both sides:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3 \amp = s(s-2)(s-2)(s-c)</mrow>
                        <mrow>3 \amp = \frac{4+c}{2} \cdot \frac{c}{2} \cdot \frac{c}{2} \cdot \frac{4-c}{2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_6nluq8ha">
                    Simplify by grouping:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3 \amp = \frac{(4+c)(4-c)}{4} \cdot \frac{c \cdot c}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>3 \amp = \frac{(16 - c^2) \cdot c^2}{16}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_f5c1uw2g">
                    Multiply both sides by 16:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>48 \amp = c^2(16 - c^2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>48 \amp = 16c^2 - c^4</mrow>
                        <mrow>c^4 - 16c^2 + 48 \amp = 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hkyj0ekw">
                    Let <m>u = c^2</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>u^2 - 16u + 48 \amp = 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_zblqyubj">
                    Factorise: we need two numbers that multiply to <m>48</m> and add to <m>-16</m>. These are <m>-4</m> and <m>-12</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>(u - 4)(u - 12) \amp = 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So <m>u = 4</m> or <m>u = 12</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_68bdevic">
                    Since <m>c^2 = u</m>, we get <m>c = \sqrt{4} = 2</m> or <m>c = \sqrt{12} = 2\sqrt{3} \approx 3.46</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ftfa0sge">
                    We check the triangle inequality: both values satisfy <m>c \lt a + b = 4</m>, so both give valid triangles.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_u32qrb19">
                    Verification: with <m>c = 2</m>, <m>s = \frac{2+2+2}{2} = 3</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{3 \times 1 \times 1 \times 1} = \sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2 \quad \checkmark</mrow>
                    </md>
                    (This is the equilateral triangle with side 2.)
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ijj7s2yy">
                    The third side is <m>2</m> cm or <m>2\sqrt{3}</m> cm.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_znpcm13k">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide a step-by-step template: (1) list <m>a, b, c</m>, (2) compute <m>s</m>, (3) compute each bracket, (4) multiply and take the square root. Start with right-angled triangles so they can verify using the standard formula.
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Complete all activities and exercises as presented, verifying Heron's Formula against the standard formula for right-angled triangles.
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Apply Heron's Formula to find the area of quadrilaterals by dividing them into two triangles. Investigate: for which triangle shape is the area maximized given a fixed perimeter?
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

